    A top tier mid-size venue
    A mid-size venue at 7,000 seats Bakkt Theater hosts the sort of act that can't fill T-Mobile but runs too big for Cosmo or The Palms, an apt description for Alice in Chains who benefited from premium acoustics across 2 hours on October 10th. Tucked at the center of Planet Hollywood both entry and exit were effortless while ushers were ubiquitous but not once obtrusive. Not quite on par with The Joint, but certainly a great place to see a show.

Sher T
Vancouver Island BC Canada eh.371 contributions
Shania fan but DON'T recommend.
Sep 2024 Couples
I'm a huge Shania fan and was excited to get tickets to see her Vegas show on Sept 4th 2024. Our seats were near the back of the theatre and cost about $100 each.

Here's the DL:

The GOOD:
-Shania is in great shape. She still fit into her original outfit from the "man I feel like a woman" video.
-the venue was nice and reasonably sized. So much better than an arena!
-songs! She played all the hits as promised.
-Shania interacted with the audience a bit including commenting on a few accents, talking about how music brings people together and bringing up a mom and a daughter in matching sparkly outfits onto the stage for a picture and to meet her.

The BAD:
-the dancers she had were distracting and unnecessary. Shania also shouldn't dance. She wore these huge platforms with these booty shorts when she first came out and, although she looked stunning, her"dance moves" etc showed her age... Just be the classy 59 year old you are, Shania. You don't have to try and be Britney.
-Most concerts offer a large screen that shows a close up of the artist for those who cannot afford to be in the front row.this venue did not offer that and even with my glasses, I couldn't see Shanias' face.
- Shania chatted in between songs... She kind of rambled, didn't make much sense. Normally I prefer the realistic, less scripted interactions between a performer and the audience but in this case, a script might have been an improvement.

The UGLY:
Shania should have taken a page from the book of Garth Brooks. He used to put on stadium shows with pyrotechnics etc in his early days but when he had his residency at the Wynn a few years back, it was literally him and his guitar singing, with limited back up fanfare. Instead Shanias' people tried to make it this huge production with flashing lights and costume changes and it just came off poorly.
-the SOUND was atrocious. Shania has a really nice voice but the background music was way too loud, had too much bass, had a weird reverberation, just terrible. Almost like they didn't do a sound check.
- the lights/laser/background videos... What the hell were they trying to do?! Strange galaxy background, neon cactus, a rocketship, a saloon... Falling flower petals?! And constant flashing lights. Just so poorly organized and thought out.
- everybody paid for seats. They didn't offer a "standing room only" or "pit" style tickets like they often do at concerts where they want the crowd to be standing or to dance etc. Instead people were encouraged to stand if they wanted to, thus blocking the view for those behind them unless they also stood. Annoying.
-It also felt kind of cheesy when she brought out some "special guests" for a photo on stage, and to sit off to the side of the stage while she performed a song. Residencies do often have VIP packages that include this kind of thing but having it overlap with the general concert is cheesy to me. VIP stuff should be BEFORE OR AFTER the concert.

Overall, we were only three songs deep and I was wondering if I could get a refund. Very disappointing. Do not recommend.
Review of: Shania Twain: Come On Over at Planet Hollywood Resort & Casino
Written September 5, 2024
